    <Descriptive_Notes>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Collector's term for Italian Renaissance X-chairs with crossing assemblies only in the front and back. Their name is derived from association with the 14th-century poet Dante, although it is questionable that such chairs were actually used by him.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>English</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000000/VP</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000099620/Legacy AAT data</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Término de coleccionista para sillas X del Renacimiento italiano con ensambles cruzados solo en el frente y respaldo. Su nombre deriva de una asociación con el poeta del siglo XIV Dante, aunque es cuestionable que tales sillas fueran realmente usadas por él.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Spanish</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000131/CDBP-SNPC</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000051034/TAA database (2000-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>Benaming van verzamelaars voor de  X-framestoelen in Italiaanse renaissancestijl met alleen aan de voor- en achterkant dwarsverbindingen. De naam is afgeleid van de dichter Dante uit de 14e eeuw, hoewel het maar de vraag is of zulke stoelen daadwerkelijk door hem werden gebruikt.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Dutch</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000205/AAT-Ned</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000113770/AAT-Ned (1994-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000052434/Termenlijst Meubelen</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000052420/Hofstede, Meubelkunst (1989)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>收藏家所用的詞彙，指稱義大利文藝復興時期的X形椅，其構件從正面與背面看起來呈交叉狀。椅子名稱由來與西元十四世紀的詩人但丁有關，然而但丁本人是否真的使用過這種椅子還有待考證。</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>Chinese (traditional)</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000250/AS-Academia Sinica</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
        <Note_Sources>
          <Note_Source>
            <Source>
              <Source_ID>2000079740/AS-Academia Sinica data (2014-)</Source_ID>
            </Source>
          </Note_Source>
        </Note_Sources>
      </Descriptive_Note>
      <Descriptive_Note>
        <Note_Text>In der Sammlersprache Bezeichnung für einen italienischen Scherenstuhl der Renaissance mit zwei gekreuzten Rippen an der Vorder- und Rückseite. Sein Name leitet sich von dem im 14. Jahrhundert lebenden Dichter Dante ab, wenngleich fraglich ist, ob ein Stuhl dieser Art tatsächlich von ihm benutzt wurde.</Note_Text>
        <Note_Language>German</Note_Language>
        <Note_Contributors>
          <Note_Contributor>
            <Contributor_id>10000232/IfM-SMB-PK</Contributor_id>
          </Note_Contributor>
        </Note_Contributors>
